# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2020-united-states-elections
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] The **116th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the Senate and the House of Representatives.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] It convened in Washington, D.C., on January 3, 2019, and ended on January 3, 2021, during the final two years of Donald Trump's first presidency.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] Senators elected to regular terms in 2014 finished their terms in this Congress, and House seats were apportioned based on the 2010 census.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] In the November 2018 midterm elections, the Democratic Party won a new majority in the House, while the Republican Party increased its majority in the Senate.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] Consequently, this was the first split Congress since the 113th Congress of 2013–2015, and the first Republican Senate–Democratic House split since the 99th Congress of 1985–1987.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] This Congress was the youngest incoming class by mean age, compared to the previous three the incoming class of freshman representatives, and the most demographically diverse in history.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] Upon joining the Libertarian Party on May 1, 2020, Justin Amash became the first member of Congress to represent a political party other than the Democrats or the Republicans since Rep.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] William Carney, who served as a Conservative before switching to the Republican Party in 1985.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] Before joining the Libertarian Party, Amash had been serving as an Independent since his departure from the Republican Party on July 4, 2019.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] Paul Mitchell also left the Republicans in December 2020, becoming an independent.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] This is the most recent Congress to feature at least one member from the Kennedy family.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] Most members of this Congress were Christian (88.2%), with approximately half being Protestant and 30.5% being Catholic.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] Other religions represented included Buddhism, Islam, and Hinduism.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] One senator said that she was religiously unaffiliated, while the number of members refusing to specify their religious affiliation increased.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] Roughly 96% of members held college degrees.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] All but 128 members were non-Hispanic white, and all but 131 members were men.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] The Senate included 74 men and 26 women, the most women to date.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] In 6 states, both senators were women; 14 states were represented by one man and one woman; and 30 states were represented by two men.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] During this Congress, Johnny Isakson retired for health reasons and Kelly Loeffler was appointed, which increased the number of women from 25 after the 2018 elections to 26.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] There were 91 non-Hispanic white, 4 Hispanic, 2 black, 2 Asian, and 1 multiracial (black/Asian) senators.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] The average age of Senators at the beginning of this Congress was 62.9 years.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] There were 101 women in the House, the largest number in history.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] There were 313 non-Hispanic white, 56 black, 44 Hispanic, 15 Asian, and 4 Native American congressmembers.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] Two Democrats — Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez and Donna Shalala — were the youngest (30) and oldest (78) freshmen women in history.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] Freshmen Rashida Tlaib (D-MI) and Ilhan Omar (DFL-MN) were the first two Muslim women and freshmen Sharice Davids (D-KS) and Deb Haaland (D-NM) were the first two Native American women elected as well.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] The average age of Members of the House at the beginning of the 116th Congress was 57.6 years.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] In addition, women chaired a record 39 House subcommittees.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] Lowey and Kay Granger were also the first women to serve as chair and ranking member of the same committee in the same Congress since the since-defunct Select Committee on the House Beauty Shop, which was chaired and populated entirely by congresswomen during its existence from 1967 to 1977.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] Congress freshmen were more diverse than any previous incoming class.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] At least 25 new congressional representatives were Hispanic, Native American, or people of color, and the incoming class included the first Native American women, the first Muslim women, and the two youngest women ever elected.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] The 116th Congress included more women elected to the House than did any previous Congress.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] The numbers refer to their Senate classes.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] All class 1 seats were contested in the November 2018 elections.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, class 1 means their term commenced in the current Congress, requiring re-election in 2024; class 2 means their term ends with this Congress, requiring re-election in 2020; and class 3 means their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 2022.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/116th-united-states-congress] Also called "elected" or "appointed" officials, there are many employees of the House and Senate whose leaders are included here.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p01] The **117th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p01] It convened in Washington, D.C., on January 3, 2021, during the final weeks of Donald Trump's first presidency and the first two years of Joe Biden's presidency and ended on January 3, 2023.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p01] The 2020 elections decided control of both chambers.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p01] In the House of Representatives, the Democratic Party retained their majority, albeit reduced from the 116th Congress.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p01] It was similar in size to the majority held by the Republican Party during the 83rd Congress (1953–1955).
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p01] Effectively, this created a 50–50 split, which had not occurred since the 107th Congress in 2001.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p01] This was only the third time in U.S. history that the Senate had been evenly split, and the longest-lasting one ever.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p01] The new senators were sworn into office by Vice President Kamala Harris, just hours after her inauguration.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p01] With Harris serving as the tie breaker in her constitutional role as President of the Senate, Democrats gained control of the Senate, and thereby full control of Congress for the first time since the 111th Congress ended in 2011.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p01] Additionally, with the inauguration of Joe Biden as president that same day, Democrats assumed control of the executive branch as well, attaining an overall federal government trifecta, also for the first time since the 111th Congress.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p01] All class 1 senators are in the middle of their term (2019–2025), having been elected in 2018 and facing re-election in 2024.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p01] Class 2 senators are at the beginning of their term (2021–2027), having been elected in 2020 and facing re-election in 2026.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p01] Class 3 senators are at the end of their term (2017–2023), having been elected in 2016 and facing re-election in 2022.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p01] All 435 seats for voting members, along with the six non-voting delegates were filled by election in November 2020.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p02] Prior to the passing of an organizing resolution on February 3, 2021, chairs of Senate committees remained the same as in the 116th Congress.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/117th-united-states-congress-p02] Where the chair had retired (as in the Agriculture, Budget, and HELP committees), the chair was vacant.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first federal elections were held in the United States following the ratification of the United States Constitution in 1788.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the elections, George Washington was elected as the first president and the members of the 1st United States Congress were selected.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Opposing them was the Anti-Administration faction, which sought a smaller role for the federal government.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In these elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Meanwhile, General George Washington was elected as the country's first president, while John Adams, who finished with the second largest number of electoral votes, was elected as the first vice president.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The presidential election of 1788–1789 was the first election of a federal head of state or head of government in United States history.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Congress of the Confederation had elected a president, but this position was one of legislative presiding officer and was not equivalent to the presidency that was established by the United States Constitution.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Constitution, the president was chosen by the Electoral College, which consisted of electors selected by each state.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Prior to the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, each elector cast two votes; the individual who received the most electoral votes would become president, while the individual who received the second-most electoral votes would become vice president.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] If no individual received votes from a majority of the electors, or if two individuals tied for the most votes, then the House of Representatives would select the president in a contingent election.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Under the Constitution, each state determines its own method of choosing presidential electors; in the 1788–1789 presidential election, many electors were appointed by state legislators, while others were chosen through elections.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In the states that did hold elections, suffrage was generally restricted to white men who owned property.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] No party made a nomination for the presidency in the 1788–1789 presidential election, but several individuals vied for electoral votes.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] After his service in the American Revolutionary War, General George Washington was the first choice of many for president, but Washington was somewhat reluctant to re-enter public service.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The American public at large, however, wanted Washington to be the nation's first president.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The first U.S. presidential campaign was, to some degree, what today would be called a grassroots effort to convince Washington to accept the office.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Alexander Hamilton was one of the most dedicated in his efforts to get Washington to accept the presidency, as he foresaw himself receiving a powerful position in the administration.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Less certain was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained little definitive job description in the constitution.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The only official role of the vice president was as the President of the United States Senate, a duty unrelated to the executive branch.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Because Washington was from Virginia, Washington (who remained neutral on the candidates) assumed that a vice president would be chosen from Massachusetts to provide sectional balance between the Northern states and the Southern states.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In an August 1788 letter, Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams, John Hancock, John Jay, James Madison, and John Rutledge to be contenders for the vice presidency.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Fearing an electoral college tie that could end with Adams winning the presidency, Alexander Hamilton arranged for several electors to vote for other candidates, including John Jay, who finished with the third most electoral votes.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] On April 6, 1789, the House and Senate, meeting in joint session, counted the electoral votes and certified that Washington had received electoral votes from each of the 69 electors that had cast votes, and thus had been elected president.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] They also certified that Adams, with 34 electoral votes, had been elected as vice president.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The other 35 electoral votes were divided among: John Jay (9), Robert H.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Harrison (6), John Rutledge (6), John Hancock (4), George Clinton (3), Samuel Huntington (2), John Milton (2), James Armstrong (1), Benjamin Lincoln (1), and Edward Telfair (1).
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Only ten of the thirteen states cast electoral votes; North Carolina and Rhode Island did not participate as they had not yet ratified the Constitution, while the New York legislature failed to appoint its allotted electors in time.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In 1788 and 1789, there were no political parties, but the major political split was between federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and anti-federalists who favored either completely rejecting the Constitution or only ratifying the document after making major changes to it.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] For example, in the election to represent Virginia's 5th congressional district, James Madison, a federalist who had played a major role in designing and ratifying the Constitution, defeated James Monroe, an anti-federalist who favored major changes to the Constitution.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] In many elections, local issues and the personal popularity of the candidates played a more important role than positions on the Constitution and other national issues.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Retrospectively, political scientists and historians have divided the 1st Congress into members of the Pro-Administration and Anti-Administration factions.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction would generally support the centralizing economic policies of the Washington administration and Secretary of State Alexander Hamilton.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction generally opposed those policies, instead favoring states' rights and a weaker federal government.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction overlapped heavily with both the federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and the later Federalist Party, while the Anti-Administration faction overlapped with the anti-federalists and the later Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Using this divide as a lens through which to view the elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1788-89-united-states-elections] Factional alignment would be fluid for much of the Washington administration.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] The first midterm elections were held in the United States in 1790 and 1791.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] They occurred in the middle of President George Washington's first term, and determined the members of the 2nd United States Congress.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Formal political parties did not exist, but Congress was broadly divided between a faction supporting the policies of the Washington administration and a faction opposed to those policies.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Despite modest gains for the anti-administration faction, the pro-administration faction retained control of both houses of Congress.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] Vermont and Kentucky joined the union during the 2nd Congress.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] In the House, neither faction made significant gains or losses, and the pro-administration faction retained control of the chamber.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1790-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the anti-administration faction picked up a moderate number of seats, but the pro-administration faction narrowly retained control of the chamber.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Elections were held for the 3rd United States Congress, in 1792 and 1793.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Congress was broadly divided between a Pro-Administration faction supporting the policies of George Washington's administration and an Anti-Administration faction opposed to those policies.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Due to this, the Federalist Party (generally overlapping with the Pro-Administration faction) and the Democratic-Republican Party (generally overlapping with the Anti-Administration faction) were starting to emerge as the distinct political parties of the First Party System.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In this election, the Pro-Administration faction maintained control of the Senate, but lost its majority in the House.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the presidential election, incumbent President George Washington was re-elected without any major opposition.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Washington had considered retirement, but was convinced to seek re-election for the purpose of national unity.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Though Washington went unchallenged, Governor George Clinton of New York sought to unseat John Adams as vice president.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] However, Adams received the second most electoral votes, and so was re-elected to office.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] Washington remained unaffiliated with any political faction or party throughout his presidency.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the House, 37 seats were added following the 1790 census.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction picked up several seats, narrowly taking the majority from the Pro-Administration faction.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] However, Frederick Muhlenberg, who leaned closer to the Pro-Administration faction, was elected Speaker of the House.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1792-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the Anti-Administration faction picked up one seat, but the Pro-Administration faction maintained a small majority.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] Elections occurred in the middle of President George Washington's second term.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] Members of the 4th United States Congress were chosen in this election.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] Tennessee was admitted as a state during the 4th Congress.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] The election took place at the beginning of the First Party System, with the Democratic-Republican Party and Federalist Party emerging as political parties, succeeding the anti-administration faction and the pro-administration faction.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] In the House, the Democratic-Republicans picked up a small number of seats, increasing their majority.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] However, Federalist Jonathan Dayton was elected Speaker of the House, defeating Frederick Muhlenberg, who had a less clear partisan affiliation.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1794-united-states-elections] In the Senate, the Federalists picked up a moderate number of seats, increasing their majority.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Elections were held for the 5th United States Congress, in 1796 and 1797.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] The election took place during the beginning stages of the First Party System, as the Federalist Party and the Democratic-Republican Party clashed over the states' rights, the financial policies of Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton, and the recently ratified Jay Treaty.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] The Federalists maintained control of the Senate, and won control of the House and the presidency.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] In the first contested presidential election and the first presidential election in which parties played a major role, Federalist Vice President John Adams narrowly defeated Democratic-Republican former Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Adams won New England while Jefferson won the South, leaving the mid-Atlantic states to decide the election.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] As the election took place prior to the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, Jefferson, who finished with the second most electoral votes, succeeded Adams as vice president.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Federalist former Governor Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina finished with the third most electoral votes, while Democratic-Republican Senator Aaron Burr of New York finished in fourth place.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] This election marked the only time in American history that members of two different political parties were elected as president and vice president.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] Adams's election made him the first member of a political party to be elected president, as George Washington had remained unaffiliated with any political faction or party throughout his presidency.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] In the House, Federalists won moderate gains, taking majority control of the chamber.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/1796-united-states-elections] In the Senate, Federalists picked up one seat, maintaining a commanding majority in the chamber.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Elections were held in the United States on November 3, 2020.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The Democratic Party's nominee, former vice president Joe Biden, defeated incumbent Republican president Donald Trump in the presidential election.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Despite losing seats in the House of Representatives, Democrats retained control of the House and very narrowly gained control of the Senate.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] As a result, the Democrats obtained a government trifecta, the first time since the elections in 2008 that the party gained unified control of Congress and the presidency.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] With Trump losing his bid for re-election, he became the first president to have seen his party lose the presidency and control of both the House and the Senate in a single term since Herbert Hoover in 1932.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] This was the first time since 1980 that either chamber of Congress flipped partisan control in a presidential year, and the first time Democrats did so since 1948.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Biden became his party's nominee after defeating numerous challengers in the Democratic primaries, while Trump faced token opposition in the Republican primaries.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In the congressional elections, Democrats lost seats in the House of Representatives but retained their majority in the chamber by a narrow margin.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats made a net gain of three seats in the Senate for a total of 50 seats, taking control of the chamber as newly elected vice-president Kamala Harris could cast tie-breaking votes.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Contests for the six non-voting congressional delegates from the District of Columbia and the permanently inhabited U.S. territories were also held during the 2020 elections.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Regularly scheduled elections were held in 86 of the 99 state legislative chambers, and 11 states held their gubernatorial elections.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Only one state governorship and two legislative chambers changed partisan control, as Republicans won the gubernatorial race in Montana and gained control of both legislative chambers in New Hampshire.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Various other state executive and judicial elections, as well as numerous referendums, tribal elections, mayoral elections, and other local elections, also took place in 2020.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The 2020 elections were the last major set of elections to impact the redistricting cycle that will take place following the 2020 census.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Significant issues for voters included the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic, as well as health care, the economy, racial unrest and climate change.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Social distancing guidelines resulted in unprecedented levels of postal voting and early voting.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Voter turnout greatly exceeded recent elections; one projection has turnout by voting eligible population being higher than any election since 1900.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] After Biden won the election, Trump and other Republicans refused to concede, making baseless and disproven claims of widespread voter fraud, despite U.S. election security officials saying that the election was "the most secure in American history".
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] These attempts to overturn the election resulted in a deadly attack on the U.S.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Capitol, which led to Trump being impeached for the second time and deplatformed across several major social media platforms.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] During the campaign, the most prominent issues were the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic, health care, economy, race, and abortion.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Trump himself held events across the country, including in COVID-19 hotspots, where attendees did not wear masks and were not socially distancing; at the same time, he mocked those who wore face masks.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans generally did not emphasize health care issues, as their opposition to the Affordable Care Act had become a political liability by 2020, as the legislation had grown in popularity.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] On the environment, Democrats proposed plans to combat climate change, including through investments in renewable energy and rejoining the Paris Climate Accords, whereas Republicans emphasized increased production of oil and natural gas.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] During the election campaign, Democrats made calls for criminal justice reform and spoke of a need to reduce systemic racism in the criminal justice system.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans ran on a "law and order" and pro-police messaging.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] While Democrats in many races were moderate, Republicans depicted them as extremists or secret "socialists" who held radical views on criminal justice or climate legislation.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The rhetoric of incumbent president Donald Trump and his allies during the election campaign was marked by frequent use of falsehoods and promotion of unfounded conspiracy theories.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In the lead-up to the elections, Republicans attacked voting rights and spread falsehoods about voter fraud.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Trump refused to commit to a peaceful transition of power in case he lost the election.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] While senior Republicans disapproved of Trump's rhetoric in private, they refused to rebuke him publicly.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The U.S. presidential election of 2020 was the 59th quadrennial U.S. presidential election, and was held to fill a term lasting from January 20, 2021, to January 20, 2025.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] By November 7, all major media organizations had projected that former vice president Joe Biden, the candidate of the Democratic Party, had defeated incumbent Republican president Donald Trump in the election.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Based on the winner of the popular vote in each state, the Electoral College cast votes on December 14, and Congress counted the electoral votes and formally declared Biden as the election winner in a joint session on January 6, 2021.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Biden won the election with 306 electoral votes and 51.3% of the national popular vote, compared to Trump's 232 electoral votes and 46.8% of the popular vote.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Biden won every state that 2016 Democratic presidential nominee Hillary Clinton won in the 2016 presidential election, as well as Arizona, Georgia, Michigan, Pennsylvania, Wisconsin, and Nebraska's second congressional district.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Biden won the tipping-point state, Wisconsin, by a margin of 0.6%.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] While Biden won the popular vote by 7 million votes, across Arizona, Georgia, and Wisconsin, the three states whose electoral votes contributed to Biden's win, Biden won by fewer than 45,000 votes.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In California and New York, Biden received 7 million more votes than Trump, accounting for Biden's popular vote win.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Among third party and independent candidates, Libertarian Party candidate Jo Jorgensen won 1.2% of the popular vote, Green Party candidate Howie Hawkins finished with 0.3% of the vote, and various other candidates won about 0.4% of the vote.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Incumbent Trump won re-nomination by his party after facing token opposition in the 2020 Republican primaries.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The Republican Party also re-nominated Vice President Mike Pence as Trump's running mate for the 2020 election.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Biden became the Democratic Party's presumptive nominee in early April 2020 after Bernie Sanders withdrew from the 2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries; Biden later chose Kamala Harris as his running mate shortly before the 2020 Democratic National Convention.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Along with Biden and Sanders, Elizabeth Warren, Michael Bloomberg, Pete Buttigieg, Amy Klobuchar, and Tulsi Gabbard all won at least one delegate in the 2020 Democratic presidential primaries.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Beyond the two major parties, about 1,200 individuals listed their names with the federal government as third party and independent candidates.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Biden is the oldest individual to win a US presidential election, and Kamala Harris is the first woman to be elected vice president of the US.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Trump's defeat made him the first incumbent president to lose re-election since George H.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Bush in the 1992 presidential election, and the tenth elected president to lose his re-election bid.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] He also became the first elected president to lose the popular vote twice since Benjamin Harrison in the late 19th century; and the first president ever to be elected while losing the popular vote, to then be impeached, and to then lose reelection as an incumbent.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The Democratic victory in the national popular vote marked the seventh time in eight elections that Democrats won the national popular vote, although Republicans won the majority of the electoral vote (and thus the election) in three of those eight elections.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Thirty-five of the 100 seats in the United States Senate were up for election in 2020: all 33 seats of Senate Class II, and seats in Arizona and Georgia that were up for special elections.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans defended 23 seats, while Democrats defended 12 seats.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Prior to the 2020 election, and including seats not up for election, Republicans held 53 Senate seats, while Democrats held 45 seats, and Democratic-aligned independents held the remaining two seats.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Because the vice president has the casting vote in the Senate, Democrats needed to achieve a net gain of at least three seats to achieve control if they won the vice presidency; otherwise, they needed to achieve a net gain of at least four seats to take the majority.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Five seats changed partisan control in the 2020 elections, as Democrats defeated both Republican incumbents in Georgia, as well as the Republican incumbents in the seats up in Arizona and Colorado.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans picked up one seat by defeating the Democratic incumbent in Alabama.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The results of the 2020 cycle left both partisan caucuses with 50 senators.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats gained majority control of the Senate on January 20, 2021, when Vice President-elect Harris and senators Alex Padilla, Jon Ossoff, and Raphael Warnock were sworn into office.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats gained control of the Senate for the first time since they lost control in the 2014 United States Senate elections.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] All 435 voting seats in the United States House of Representatives were up for election; 218 seats are necessary for a majority.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The winners of each race serve a two-year term.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats had gained control of the House of Representatives in the 2018 elections, winning 235 seats compared to 199 seats for Republicans.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Due to vacancies and party-switching that arose during the 116th Congress, immediately before the November 2020 elections Democrats held 232 seats, compared to 197 seats held by Republicans and one seat, that of Justin Amash, held by the Libertarian Party.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Thus, Republicans needed to gain 21 seats to gain a majority.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans picked up 14 seats in the House elections, defeating thirteen incumbent House Democrats.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Nationally, Democratic House candidates won by a margin of about 3%, as many Democrats ran behind Biden.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The election results left Democrats with a narrow majority of 222 seats at the start of the 117th Congress.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Five special elections were held in 2020 to replace a member who resigned or died in office during the 116th U.S.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Elections were held for the governorships of 11 U.S. states and two U.S. territories.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Most elections were for four-year terms, but the governors of New Hampshire and Vermont each serve two-year terms.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans defended a total of seven seats, while Democrats defended six seats.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Only one state governorship changed parties, as Republican Greg Gianforte won the 2020 Montana gubernatorial election, succeeding outgoing Democratic governor Steve Bullock.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In Puerto Rico, the governorship was retained by the New Progressive Party, although the winning candidate, Pedro Pierluisi, is affiliated with the Democratic Party, replacing an incumbent who was affiliated with the Republican Party.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Regularly scheduled elections were held in 86 of the 99 state legislative chambers in the United States; nationwide, regularly scheduled elections were held for 5,876 of the 7,383 legislative seats.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Many legislative chambers had all legislative seats up for election, but some legislative chambers that use staggered elections held elections for only a portion of the total seats in the chamber.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Although most states held regularly scheduled elections for both legislative chambers, Alabama, Louisiana, Maryland, Mississippi, New Jersey and Virginia did not hold state legislative elections, and Michigan held elections only for the lower house.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Nebraska, the only state that does not have a bicameral state legislature, held elections for half of the seats in its lone legislative chamber.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] A total of two legislative chambers changed partisan control in 2020, as Republicans gained control of both chambers in New Hampshire.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] This represented the fewest partisan changes in state legislatures since 1944.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Prior to the November 2020 elections, Democrats held 15 "trifectas" (control of the governor's office and both legislative chambers), Republicans held 20 trifectas, and 14 states have a divided government.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Not included in this tally is Nebraska, as its legislature officially recognizes no party affiliations.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Nationwide, Republicans controlled approximately 60 percent of the legislative chambers and 52 percent of the legislative seats.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The 2020 elections created two new trifectas, as the New Hampshire and Montana state government shifted from divided government to Republican control.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Regularly scheduled elections were held in 10 of 43 states that elect attorneys general.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The previous attorney general elections for this group of states took place in 2016, except in Vermont where attorneys general only serve two-year terms and last elected their current attorney general in 2018.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Nine state attorneys general ran for re-election and eight won, while Republican Tim Fox of Montana could not run again due to term limits and Republican Curtis Hill of Indiana was eliminated in the Republican convention.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] No attorneys general offices changed party control in 2020.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Regularly scheduled elections were held in 7 of 35 states that elect secretaries of states.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The previous secretary of state elections for this group of states took place in 2016, except in Vermont where secretaries of state only serve two-year terms and last elected their current secretary of state in 2018.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Five state secretaries of state ran for re-election and all five won, while Republicans Corey Stapleton of Montana and Bev Clarno of Oregon chose to retire.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats picked up the secretary of state office in Oregon.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Regularly scheduled elections were held in nine states.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The previous state treasurer elections for this group of states took place in 2016, except in Vermont where state treasurers only serve two-year terms and last elected their current state treasurer in 2018.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Eight state treasurers ran for re-election and five won, while Republican Kelly Schmidt of North Dakota chose to retire.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans picked up the state treasurer offices in Pennsylvania and West Virginia.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] While Democrats picked up the state treasurer office in Washington.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In 2020, 82 state supreme court seats are up for election in 35 states.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] This constitutes 24% of all state supreme court seats in the country.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Various other state courts will also hold elections in 2020.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Various state executive positions are also up for election in 2020.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In the 2020 elections, voters considered a number of referendums, initiatives, ballot measures, and state constitutional amendments on a variety of topics, ranging from Medicaid expansion to marijuana legalization to voting rights.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Since the murder of George Floyd and subsequent protests, there were at least 20 police-related ballot measures across the country, including in California, Illinois, Ohio, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Texas, and Washington.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Several proposed referendums failed to secure the necessary number of signatures to appear on ballots due to disruptions and social distancing measures undertaken after the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] These included an effort in Ohio to raise the state's hourly minimum wage from $8.70 to $13; an anti-gerrymandering efforts in Oklahoma and Arkansas; and a California effort to allow electronic signatures for future California ballot measures.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Following the 2020 United States census, the state delegations to the U.S.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] House of Representatives will undergo reapportionment, and both the U.S.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] House of Representatives and the state legislatures will undergo redistricting.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In states without redistricting commissions, the legislators and governors elected between 2017 and 2020 will draw the new congressional and state legislative districts that will take effect starting with the 2022 elections.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] State supreme courts can also have a significant effect on redistricting, as demonstrated in states such as Pennsylvania and Virginia.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Thus the 2020 elections had a significant impact on the 2020 United States redistricting cycle.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Barring court orders or mid-decade redistricting, the districts drawn in the redistricting cycle will remain in place until the next round of redistricting begins in 2030.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In the 2020 elections, the Republican Party won several legislative chambers and gubernatorial positions that had been selected by Democrats as key redistricting targets.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Republicans also retained control of the Pennsylvania legislature and Minnesota Senate, ensuring divided partisan control of redistricting in both states.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Additionally, the passage of a referendum in Virginia removed control of redistricting from the Democratic-controlled legislature to an independent commission.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] However, in New York, Democrats gained a two-thirds super-majority in the State Senate and held their super-majority in the State Assembly, giving the party full control of redistricting.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The U.S. territories of American Samoa and Puerto Rico held gubernatorial and legislative elections in 2020, while Guam, the Northern Mariana Islands, and the U.S.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Virgin Islands held legislative elections.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Along with Washington, D.C., each territory also held elections for a non-voting delegate to the U.S.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] All non-voting delegates serve two-year terms, with the exception of the Resident Commissioner of Puerto Rico, a non-voting position with a four-year term.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Washington, D.C., also held elections for its shadow representative and one of its two shadow senators.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The five territories also took part in the 2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries and the 2020 Republican Party presidential primaries.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In Norfolk, Virginia, Mayor Kenny Alexander was unopposed in seeking reelection, as was Mayor John Cruz in Hagåtña, Guam.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Bynum earned reelection by winning an outright majority in the August primary.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In Baltimore, Maryland, city council president Democrat Brandon Scott was elected to replace incumbent Democrat Jack Young who came in fifth in a crowded primary.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In Stockton, California, Kevin Lincoln defeated one-term incumbent mayor Michael Tubbs, who was first Black mayor of the city and the youngest person elected to the position when he unseated incumbent mayor Anthony Silva in 2016.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In Texas, two mayoral runoff elections in December saw incumbents defeated: In Corpus Christi, city councilwoman Paulette Guajardo defeated incumbent Joe McComb, and in El Paso, former mayor Oscar Leeser unseated one-term incumbent Dee Margo.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In Ely, Minnesota, Eric Urbas defeated three-term incumbent mayor Chuck Novack despite Urbas having dropped out of the race in August.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In Rabbit Hash, Kentucky, incumbent Brynneth Pawltro was ousted by Wilbur Beast, a 6-month-old French bulldog.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The town has never had a human mayor; Pawltro is a pit bull terrier.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Several mayors faced recall campaigns during 2020.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Mayors in Broken Bow, Nebraska; Diamond City, Arkansas; Heyburn, Idaho; and Oregon City, Oregon, were removed from office.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Mayors in Elizabeth and Idaho Springs, Colorado; Humboldt, Nebraska; Powers, Oregon; Stevensville, Montana; and Westminster, California were retained in office.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] A number of Native American tribal governments held elections for tribal leadership in 2020.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] As with other elections in the country, the coronavirus pandemic disrupted many elections, delaying primaries and shifting some voting from in-person to postal.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The Fort McDowell Yavapai Nation reelected President Bernadine Burnette; the Sault Ste.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Marie Tribe of Chippewa Indians reelected Tribal Chairman Aaron A.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Stephanie Bryan, the first woman to serve as chair of the Poarch Band of Creek Indians, also won reelection.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] United Keetoowah Band of Cherokee Indians incumbent Tribal Chief Joe Bunch, who was impeached but not removed from office in January 2020, was re-elected.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In a runoff election, former South Dakota state senator Kevin Killer defeated incumbent Oglala Lakota Tribe president Julian Running Bear, who made the runoff by a single vote after surviving an impeachment effort in September.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Crow Nation Senator Frank White Clay defeated incumbent tribal chairman A.J.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Kristopher Peters was elected Squaxin Island Tribe tribal council chairman, defeating incumbent Arnold Cooper, and Joseph Tali Byrd defeated long-time Quapaw Nation Business Committee Chairman John Berrey.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Durell Cooper defeated incumbent Apache Tribe of Oklahoma Tribal Chairman Bobby Komardley.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Echo-Hawk was unopposed in a special election for president of the Pawnee Nation of Oklahoma Business Council following the April 2020 recall of the prior president, James Whiteshirt.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The Shakopee Mdewakanton Sioux Community elected Keith Anderson tribal chairman, replacing the retiring Charlie Vig.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Northern Cheyenne voters elected five women to the tribal council, along with electing Donna Marie Fisher as tribal president and Serena Wetherelt as vice president.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] It is the first time women will make up the majority on the Northern Cheyenne tribal council.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Starting in March 2020, elections across the United States were delayed and disrupted by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Numerous states delayed presidential primaries, while Alabama delayed the Republican primary Senatorial run-off and North Carolina and Mississippi delayed Republican primary run-off for congressional seats.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Iowa, Missouri, South Carolina, and Texas all delayed municipal elections, and in New York City the special election for Queens borough president was cancelled.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The pandemic also led to the postponement of the 2020 Democratic National Convention, and both the 2020 Democratic National Convention and the 2020 Republican National Convention were held virtually.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] To help enforce social distancing, many states expanded absentee and vote-by-mail options for 2020 primary elections and the November general elections.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Several elections, including Democratic primaries in Alaska and Hawaiʻi, as well as the Maryland 7th congressional district special election, were conducted entirely with mail-in ballots only.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] While the pandemic was impacting a number of things in elections 2020, Donald Trump was reported of planning to host his Election Night party at the White House.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Two officials informed that Trump was planning a large indoor party of nearly 400 people at the East Room.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The Trump Hotel on Pennsylvania Avenue was initially chosen as the venue, but this was later changed due to COVID-19 restrictions that limited such gatherings to 50 people.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] With many states easing rules on early voting in the midst of the COVID-19 pandemic, the 2020 election saw an unprecedented rate of early voting.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] By October 26, with eight days remaining until the election, the total early vote throughout the United States had eclipsed that of 2016.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In total, about 100 million voters cast early votes, compared to the approximately 57 million early votes cast in 2016.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Democrats disproportionately voted by mail, while Republicans tended to vote more frequently in person.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Just under 160 million people voted in the 2020 elections, compared to a turnout of approximately 137 million in the 2016 presidential election.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] Michael McDonald projects that about 67% of the voting eligible population voted in 2020, the highest rate of voter participation since the 1952 election.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] The 2020 elections saw the highest rate of voter participation by voting eligible population since the ratification of the Voting Rights Act of 1965, which prohibits racial discrimination in voting, and the Twenty-sixth Amendment, which effectively lowered the national voting age from 21 to 18.
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In a poll conducted in 2019, 59% of respondents expressed that they are not confident in the "honesty of U.S. elections".
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] In an August 2020 survey, 49% of respondents said that they expect voting to be "difficult", up from 15% in 2018; 75% of Republicans, but less than half of Democrats were confident that the elections "will be conducted fairly and accurately".
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] 49% of college students polled in September 2020 said that the elections won't be "fair and open", 55% that "it will not be administered well", and 81% that "special interest groups have more influence over election outcomes than voters".
[src:2020-united-states-elections/2020-united-states-elections-p01] According to an October 2020 poll, eight out of ten Americans consider misinformation a "major problem"; Biden supporters were more likely than Trump supporters to trust the news media and their candidate's messaging.
